******
[3] Vaccination started
Date: Sat 25 Dec 2010
Source: Korea Herald [summarized, edited]
<http://www.koreaherald.com/national/Detail.jsp?newsMLId=20101225000038>


South Korea starts vaccinating cattle against FMD
-------------------------------------------------
South Korea begun inoculating cattle in 5 cities against FMD as part
of its efforts to curb further spread of the animal disease,
government officials said Saturday [25 Dec 2010].

The Ministry for Food, Agriculture, Forestry and Fisheries announced
Wednesday its program to vaccinate cattle against the contagion after
the ministry failed to prevent it from spreading across the country.
As of Saturday, a total of 56 cases were reported, leading a mass
cull of 330 000 animals.

Despite a cold wave hitting the country for a 2nd day, the
vaccination was conducted smoothly in 5 cities -- Andong and Yecheon,
the cities of North Gyeongsang Province and Paju, Goyang, Yeoncheon,
the cities of Gyeonggi Provinces, the ministry said.

About 133 000 cattle were vaccinated, the ministry said, adding that
it plans to wrap up the vaccination within 3 or 4 days at the earliest.

--
Communicated by:
ProMED-mail
<promed@promedmail.org>

[Further details on the vaccination plans, performance and follow-up
will be posted when available. Data on the source of the vaccine and
the vaccine-strain applied will be helpful. According to the
information of the WRLFMD (IAH, Pirbright), the reference virus most
closely related to a serotype O strain isolated in S. Korea on 8 Apr
2010 is named O/MYA/7/98, a Malaysian SEA genotype/strain, topotype
Mya-98 (identity percentage 93.74; see at
<http://www.wrlfmd.org/fmd_genotyping/2010/WRLFMD-2010-0000H%20O%20South%20Korea%202010.pdf>).

The vaccination of 133 000 heads of cattle in one day may have become
feasible by the activation, as planned, of 200 teams (mean 665
head/team). This will, most likely, protect those animals but will
not prevent further spread of the virus from the unvaccinated pig population.

Large-scale vaccinations against the similar virus strain which was
involved in the 2010 outbreaks in Hong-Kong, South Korea (April/May),
Japan, Mongolia and Russia, have been recently undertaken in
Mongolia. In Japan, a "vaccination to kill" policy was applied [see
archived 20100519.1646]. The mainland China FMD situation,
particularly genotyping and vaccine application, are less transparent.

So far, 2 official reports on the 2010 FMD epizootic in Japan have
been published (in Japanese). Both were somewhat critical to their
mother organisations. They are:

[1] Intermediate Report of FMD in Miyazaki, by the 'Verification
Committee for FMD in Miyazaki, Miyazaki Prefecture Government',
published 29 Oct 2010. PDF, 11 pages 176KB, available at
<http://www.pref.miyazaki.lg.jp/parts/000148486.pdf>. The full report
is expected early Jan 2011.

[2] Report of Verification Committee for FMD Countermeasures, by the
'Verification Committee for FMD Countermeasures: Independent
Committee in the Ministry of Agriculture, Forestry and Fisheries',
published on 24 Nov 2010. PDF, 50 pages, 1.76MB, available at
<http://www.maff.go.jp/j/syouan/douei/katiku_yobo/k_fmd/pdf/kensyo_hokoku_sho.pdf>.


ProMED-mail is grateful to the Japanese source who responded to our
RFI and brought those reports to our attention. -Mod.AS]
